The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, July 14, 2004 				 Car sales on fast track in June
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, July 13: Passenger car sales leapt 24.9 per cent in June to 65,046 units, helped by lower interest rates and speculation that the government will levy a tax surcharge that will drive up prices.																								The Society of Indian Automobile Manufacturers (SIAM) today said sales in April-June, the first quarter of the financial year to March, rose 21.5 per cent to 1,81,936 units from 1,49,724 a year earlier.																								Thirteen automakers, including the local subsidiaries of global firms like Suzuki, Hyundai, General Motors and Ford, makes cars, vans and utility vehicles in the country.																								The Indian unit of the US-based General Motors, Honda India, and Japans Suzuki Motor Companys Maruti Udyog reported higher sales. 																								Hyundai Motor Indias Accent sedan, however, reported a lower sales of 1,602 units in June against 2,135 units a year-ago along with Hindustan Motors Lancer sedan and Fiat India. 
